ce:section.ce:para:
The microstructure inside the Im-PSU membrane and the nanocomposite AEMs was characterized by TEM. As shown in Fig. 5
                           , the shaded area in the image represents the hydrophilic phase region of the composite membranes, while the bright white region represents the hydrophobic phase region of the composite membranes. The pure polymer membrane has fewer hydrophilic ion clusters as shown in Fig. 5a. When the QCDs content is increased to 1.0 wt% (Fig. 5c), the hydrophilic ion clusters are significantly increased and dispersed uniformly. However, when the content of QCDs increases to 5.0 wt%, the doping phase begins to display obvious agglomeration (see Fig. 5d). The main reason for the above results may be that the QCDs with the high specific surface area can bring more quaternary ammonium groups to the composite membranes, thus forming more hydrophilic ion clusters, and highly concentrated ion clusters can generate long-range ordered ion transport channels (see Scheme 3
                           ), thereby improving the ion conductivity of the composite membranes [36,39]. However, excessive QCDs are easily aggregated due to too close distance, thereby destroying the ion transport channel and may reduce the ion conductivity of the nanocomposite AEMs.
